diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Hypoglycemia is common, especially in those on insulin or certain oral agents, and dyslipidemia is a frequent comorbidity.

diagnoses.name: Pancreatitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause migratory abdominal pain. Dyslipidemia, particularly hypertriglyceridemia, is a risk factor. Hypoglycemia may occur in severe cases due to pancreatic islet cell damage.

diagnoses.name: Cystic Fibrosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic condition that can lead to hypoglycemia (due to pancreatic insufficiency), dyslipidemia, and wheezing due to lung involvement.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Wheezing is a prominent symptom. The systemic inflammation associated with COPD may contribute to dyslipidemia.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized by wheezing. Severe asthma can influence blood lipid levels indirectly through systemic inflammation or directly as a side effect of systemic corticosteroids.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause wheezing due to aspiration and migratory abdominal pain. The relationship to hypoglycemia and dyslipidemia is indirect but can be related to medications or dietary management.

diagnoses.name: Familial Hypercholesterolemia
diagnoses.reasoning: A genetic disorder causing severe dyslipidemia. While directly unrelated to hypoglycemia, wheezing, or abdominal pain, patients can have a constellation of symptoms influenced by the underlying metabolic disruptions.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism can disturb lipid metabolism, leading to dyslipidemia. Hypothyroidism can indirectly cause hypoglycemia. Abdominal pain and wheezing can occur, particularly in severe cases or related autoimmune conditions.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause migratory abdominal pain. Dyslipidemia can occur as part of the chronic inflammation process. Hypoglycemia may occur in the context of malnutrition associated with severe disease.

diagnoses.name: Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: A condition caused by gastrin-secreting tumors that can lead to migratory abdominal pain due to peptic ulcers. While hypoglycemia and dyslipidemia are not primary symptoms, the complex interplay of hormone imbalances can impact overall metabolic health.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can lead to hypotension, hypoxia, and abdominal cramps.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.description: Loss of fluids, often from vomiting or diarrhea, can cause hypotension, syncope, and hypoxia due to reduced blood volume.

diagnoses.name: Sepsis
diagnoses.description: A body-wide response to infection that can cause hypotension, hypoxia, and abdominal cramps.

diagnoses.name: Addison's disease
diagnoses.description: An endocrine disorder where the adrenal glands do not produce enough steroid hormones, leading to abdominal cramps, hypotension, and syncope.

diagnoses.name: Toxic shock syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections that can cause hypotension, syncope, and abdominal cramps.

diagnoses.name: Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the stomach and intestines that can cause abdominal cramps, hypotension (due to dehydration), and hypoxia if severe.

diagnoses.name: Heart arrhythmias
diagnoses.description: Irregular heartbeats can lead to syncope and hypotension.

diagnoses.name: Pneumonia
diagnoses.description: An infection that inflames the air sacs in one or both lungs which can cause hypoxia and, in severe cases, hypotension and abdominal cramps due to toxin release.

diagnoses.name: Vasovagal syncope
diagnoses.description: A sudden drop in heart rate and blood pressure leading to fainting, commonly in response to a stressor like sight of blood or extreme emotional distress.

diagnoses.name: Acute adrenal crisis
diagnoses.description: A life-threatening condition that occurs when there is not enough cortisol, leading to abdominal cramps, hypotension, and syncope.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by severe head pain followed or accompanied by sensory disturbances such as flashes of light, blind spots, tingling in the arms and legs, nausea, vomiting, and increased sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a brief period of symptoms similar to those in a stroke. A TIA doesn't cause permanent damage. Symptoms mirror those of a stroke and can include paralysis, speech difficulties, and mental confusion.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms may include trouble walking, speaking, and understanding, as well as paralysis or numbness of the face, arm, or leg.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Specific types of epilepsy may present with these symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It may present with vision problems, paralysis, and sensory issues like tingling or numbness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. It may present with headaches, seizures, speech difficulties, paralysis, and other neurological symptoms depending on its location and size.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include severe headache, fever, stiff neck, nausea, vomiting, confusion and, in severe cases, seizures.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a blood vessel in the brain leaks or ruptures. Besides the common stroke symptoms, it may also cause severe headaches.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Symptoms vary but can include fatigue, joint pain, rash, and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that causes changes in the blood vessel walls. Symptoms can include headaches, fever, fatigue, weight loss, and general weakness.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It's frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.details: A condition that occurs when you use or lose more fluid than you take in, and your body doesn't have enough water and other fluids to carry out its normal functions.

diagnoses.name: Viral Gastroenteritis (Stomach Flu)
diagnoses.details: An intestinal infection marked by watery diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea or vomiting, and sometimes fever.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: A condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues, causing fatigue and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Vertigo (Peripheral Vertigo)
diagnoses.details: Often a result of a problem with the part of the inner ear that controls balance. Symptoms can include dizziness and spinning sensation.

diagnoses.name: Tension Headache
diagnoses.details: The most common type of headache. It causes mild, moderate, or intense pain behind the eyes, head, and neck.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.details: A condition caused by a very low level of blood sugar (glucose), which is your body’s main energy source.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: A disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It can cause weakness, lack of coordination, and trouble maintaining balance.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Symptoms can include headaches, seizures, and changes in personality.

diagnoses.name: Medication Side Effects
diagnoses.details: Various medications can lead to symptoms like weakness, headache, and vertigo, depending on how the body reacts to them.

diagnoses: Drug Reactions (e.g., Stevens-Johnson Syndrome, Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reason: SLE can manifest with a wide range of symptoms including skin rashes (including a psoriaform rash), thrombocytopenia, and proteinuria due to lupus nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.reason: Characterized by skin changes, including rash and telangiectasias, and could potentially indirectly cause proteinuria through kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma (Systemic Sclerosis)
diagnoses.reason: Scleroderma could lead to skin changes (telangiectasias, panniculitis), renal crisis (which may present as proteinuria), and can sometimes be associated with thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: This condition leads to thrombocytopenia and can show skin manifestations like a rash. Renal involvement might manifest as proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.reason: Can include features of systemic lupus erythematosus, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis including skin rash, thrombocytopenia, and proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.reason: This vasculitis often presents with a purpuric rash, abdominal pain, and can involve the kidneys, leading to proteinuria. Though more common in children, it can also occur in adults.

diagnoses.name: Cryoglobulinemia
diagnoses.reason: Can cause skin manifestations such as purpura and panniculitis, kidney disease (proteinuria), and can be associated with thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.reason: Various forms of vasculitis can result in skin changes, renal involvement (proteinuria), and potentially low platelet counts.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.reason: Primarily affects the skin (psoriasis) and joints, but systemic involvement can include kidney disease manifesting as proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: Primarily a connective tissue disorder, some forms can feature skin manifestations including panniculitis and telangiectasias. It's less commonly associated with the renal or hematologic symptoms mentioned but could potentially present with overlapping symptoms or secondary complications.
